Basing on the picture, I thought this was a buffet restaurant; instead it's the down to earth turo turo. So, if you're looking for a Filipino restaurant with ambiance, this is not the place you'd like to go and definitely not a place to bring someone whose just visiting. The bathroom is very clean beyond expectation.< /Text>

<Time>1609650091368</Time><username>Scott Delgado<//username>< review>
This was my first time ordering from Ameci. I had heard good things.

The delivery guy couldn't figure out how to get to the elevator of my apartment, so I put on a jacket and walked for 4 minutes to go down three floors to meet him despite the order saying it would be left on my doorstep.  The $4.50 delivery fee and tip I paid up front felt a bit unearned. Then when I get the food up to my apartment, I see the salad is not the salad I ordered. Fine. I pick off the meat and peppers. Then I (foolishly) poor the dressing over the salad. I ordered Blue Cheese. Then I notice the Blue Cheese is a bit thin--because I was given Ranch dressing.

The pizza tastes good. But I'm not sure it's worth all the mix ups. I thought I'd try someplace new to me. I can say I tried it. Again, the pizza tastes good. Yay for that.< /review>

<Text>Decent Italian food and it's a good bang for the buck. I have eaten almost all their food items except for a dish with sausages and broccoli, a meat lasagna dish, and a couple other items.
This of course has spanned about 11 years.
My first experience with Ameccis was in Fountain Valley at Magnolia and Talbert, where the first thing I tried was linguini and clams... Superb. Then I tried other items.
I was so glad to find them at a location in Irvine, as I was doing business for a few weeks there.
They are franchises and I think the consistency of quality at each franchise is remarkable.
They have a nice lunch specials, great pizza, and plenty of individual items.
Their prices have not really increased over the years, however, I do believe and I suspect the circular tins they put their food in has gotten a bit smaller. I just remember the portions weighed maybe 15% more and seemed bigger 10 years ago. It's just an observation and not really a knock because their food is so good.<//Text>< resp>
None< /resp>

< review>
Absolutely love this place. The price is what you'd expect for all-you-can-eat and the quality is really good. <Name>Michelle Wagner</Name><Date>1578626479356<//Date>< rate>
2<//rate>
< review>
Love, love their Pinots.  I visited the tasting room in Sonoma solo one day on an impromptu visit.

As a single woman, I was surprisingly treated respectfully and I almost thought that they might have thought I was an insider, since it was during the week.  It was memorable.

I tried to recapture the experience of a quiet and contemplative tasting experience at the newly opened room across from Oxbow in Napa where the Ahnfeldt‚Äôs Uncorked used to be on First.

It was awful.  I will not go back there despite the fact that the Pinots are some of the best I‚Äôve tasted.  We were peppered with 20 questions from the start of our visit to the end.  I almost felt like I was being interrogated by the young server.  Horrible.  I thought I was paying her for wine and the experience, but instead she seemed to be pumping my group for information.

Awful.....get it together Walt Napa, because the Pinots are actually some of the best Northern California showcases....<//review>

<Rating>4<//Rating>< text>
Came to WALT because they had been pouring wine at our hotel the night before.  The tasting room is a quaint old Victorian house just off the main square in Sonoma.  With a small room, they have a few tables in the "living room" space and tasting attendants bring wine to you.  The staff is excellent and you don't feel rushed at any point.  The pours are also very generous.  If you are out wine tasting anywhere near Sonoma this is a great stop on your trip.< /text>

Great new beer bar right across from the Muni in San Francisco. With open windows, dark lighting, and a long bar, it's easy to sit, sip on a cold beer and chat with a friend. < review>
I visited Triple Voodoo's taproom on Sunday afternoon (10/20/17). I had a slight concern, and was promptly contacted by one of the owners named Aaron. Aaron helped answer all my questions and concerns, and was very happy to do so. The level of professionalism shown by Aaron and his team really showed me how much the owners and staff at Triple Voodoo care about their beer and taproom experience. Triple Voodoo is the type of local business I will gladly support due to the quality and care they put into their business.

As for the beer, I had the Tropical Sundowner, which is a fruited kettle sour. This particular beer was very good, and I even got a 32oz growler fill of it since I loved the taste. It had a tart/sour taste, but was not overly sour. I think both fans and critics of sour beers would enjoy a glass of Tropical Sundowner. My wife had a Belgian style beer which she really enjoyed too . Unfortunately we were short on time, so I wasn't able to experience the many other beers offered at the taproom, but there was a fairly large selection to chose from. There were many varieties to chose from such as IPAs, stouts and German style beers. Triple Voodoo has enough variety of beer styles to appease all beer drinkers.

I will definitely be back to Triple Voodoo with friends and family the next time I am in San Francisco. It's a great place to drink craft beer in the city with a local feel to it. Stop by when you're in town!</review>
